Wherein Captain Kirby Spends Way Too Much Time Dissecting An Article


08 Jun 2018 22:20






Gaaaah. I have so much to say about this skip. So much I like, and so much that irks me. Like, this isn't a bad article, but like ok let me explain.

Theopinion)

–block


First of all, this is a pretty top tier hook. 

But then we get into the meat of the article. If I were to summarize what this skip excels at, its atmosphere and tension. The imagery of constantly going down an elevator into this unknown sector is quite evocative, and the minimalism shown in each of the room descriptions is quite powerful. It does a great job of raising questions.

Furthermore, there's a really nice build, where each level feels like an escalation of the previous floor. It's hard for me to pin down what exactly causes this feeling, but I can definitely feel it. This way, when you get to the end, you can just feel yourself about to explode from the anticipation.






The:P)

–block


As I said previously, this article does a really good job at raising questions, and building tension. However, it feels like it doesn't actually do anything more than that. The questions we have are great, but my issue is that we aren't given enough information to really speculate on it. I don't think this article needs to give any concrete answers, but I know that after I read that final entry, I did not have the  moment I was expecting.

I say this because when I feel that there are so many questions left unanswered, I either need more context to speculate, or something else to make me really understand the gravitas of the situation. Sure, this is incredibly mysterious, and it has to be important to be sealed under O5 control, but if there's nothing to remind me/reaffirm that gravitas at the end, the tension built won't have anywhere to go.

That's my issue with the article. It's not the lack of answers, or the vagueness on its own. It's how this tension is not reaffirmed at the end of the article. It doesn't feel like a conclusion so much as the article just stopping.






Suggestion,ignoring

–block


Even though this has been posted, I'm still making this suggestion: in the description, you mention how there are six accessible floors, but there's obviously a seventh floor that we can't get to. Don't say that we can't get to the seventh floor in the description. Just note that there are seven floors. Then, when you do the 

Just moving this detail to the end gives the reader the  which seeeems like its one of the takeaways you want from this. Because right now, that information is left up and the beginning, and at least I did not remember about the 7th floor when I originally hit the end. It feels like it would be powerful to end with a more obviously posed question, so the reader has a more obvious takeaway.




Aaaaaand that's all I got. Was this a lot? Yes. Was it worth it? Idk but I had fun writing it. Right now I'm at a novote, and I know its not like you're looking for crit or seeing if things need changing, but fwiw if you make the change I've suggested, that would definitely move me to an upvote.







